voice_to_text: The Soviet officer grabbed two little puppies. Then he tossed the puppies under a tank. The mother dog saw what happened. She also rushed under the tank. It turned out the officer was training the dogs to destroy enemy armor. But many soldiers couldn't accept this. One soldier tried to walk away with his dog. The officer fired a warning shot. Then he shouted at all the soldiers. They didn't use the dogs to take out tanks. More soldiers would end up being lost. The soldiers had no choice but to obey. They locked all the dogs up. For six straight day. They were given only water, no food. Then the soldiers tossed food under the tank. The starving dogs rushed straight under the tank. To get the dogs used to the roaring sound of tanks, a soldier even risked his life and crawled under a moving tank himself. Seeing its handler in danger, the dog immediately rushed under the tank as well. Soon all the dogs stopped, fearing the tank noise. Then the soldiers strapped special explosive devices onto the dogs. Once they made contact with the underside of a tank, the device would trigger instantly. The soldiers then brought the dogs to the front lines. The enemy launched an assault with infantry and tanks together. For Tiger tanks advanced toward the Soviets. The officer ordered the release of the dogs carrying charges. One soldier reluctantly said goodbye to his dog. Then he unclipped the harness, threw a hail Of enemy fire. The dog dashed under the tank and successfully destroyed one German tank. The soldier was heartbroken, but the remaining three tanks kept pushing toward the Soviet lines. But commander ordered a second charge carrying dog to be released. With another massive blast, another dog gave its life. By now, the enemy tanks had reached the front of the Soviet position. The commander again ordered the release of a dog. A soldier couldn't bear to send his dog to die, so he grabbed the explosive pack from the dog and ran straight toward the enemy tank. The the officer rushed out to stop him, but unfortunately the soldier was hit by enemy fire. Then the officer was struck as well. As the tank rolled toward them, the officer triggered the charge and destroyed the third tank. The last enemy tank began firing repeatedly at the Soviet position. Many soldiers were knocked down by the blasts. One soldier couldn't bear to release another dog. He rushed out ready to fight the enemy himself. But he was shot by enemy fire. Seeing its handler fall, the dog bravely charged toward the tank. It rushed underneath it, successfully destroying the last tank. This is a true story. The Soviets trained 40,000 dogs during World War 2. Throughout the entire war, the dogs took out more than 300 enemy tanks.

voice_to_text: I planned an international travel without my children. I've got two kids, 16 and 14 now. When me and their mom split up six years ago, we did the whole 50 50 thing, week on, week off. It was fine. The kids adjusted. I had them half the time, she had them half the time. Nobody was complaining. Then 4 years ago, my ex got remarried. Her new husband convinced her to go back to court and fight for more custody. I still don't know why. Maybe he wanted to play stepdad of the year. Maybe they just wanted child support money. Whatever the reason, she filed. I had to hire a lawyer, then another one. When the first guy turned out to be useless, 4 years of court dates, mediations, evaluations, therapy sessions for the kids. The Bill kept climbing. By the time we finally went to trial last spring, I had spent $165,000. That was everything I had saved. My retirement fund, gone. The money I was putting away for the kids college, gone. Every dollar I scraped together from overtime and side jobs, gone. My ex didn't pay a cent. Her dad is loaded and he covered all her legal fees. Must be nice. The court made the kids talk to a therapist. The older one, my 16 year old, told them straight up that they wanted to live with mom full time and only see me every other weekend. The younger one said they still wanted 50. 50 at first. Then a few weeks later they changed their mind and said maybe 70, 30 with mom would be better. Said they just wanted the court stuff to be over. I get it. Four years is a long time for kids to deal with that, but it still hurt. We went to trial in June. My lawyer actually did a good job, presented everything properly, pointed out that there was no reason to change custody, that I've been a good parent the whole time, didn't matter. The judge said that given their ages, the kids'preference was the most important factor and she wasn't going to split them up because that would damage their sibling bond or whatever. So that's how I ended up with every other weekend four years and $165,000 later, I get to see my kids four days a month. My wife and I needed something to look forward to after all that. Her sister suggested we do a trip with her and her husband and some of their friends. Nine days in Spain and France, Barcelona, Madrid, Paris. We've been talking about doing something like this for years but never actually pulled the trigger. They picked the dates in October. We all booked tickets, got an Airbnb in Barcelona and hotel rooms in Madrid and Paris. My wife's sister's family was bringing their 15 year old son. We planned hiking, museums, trying actual Spanish food, all of it. The kids came over for their Weekend in September, they were in the kitchen while I was making dinner and my younger one saw the tickets printed out on the counter. They picked it up and said, what's this? I told them it was for a trip we had planned. My older one looked over their shoulder and said, Spain? You're going to Spain? I said, yes. They both started talking at once, when are you going? How long can we come? Why didn't you tell us? I explained that this was something me and my wife planned with her family, that we've been saving up for it and it was already booked. My younger one said, but we wanna go.

voice_to_text: My neighbor left her six children on my doorstep, I sent her a video of her children being picked up by child services. We live in a cul de sac where everyone knows everything about everyone. My neighbor Amber has six kids ranging from 6 months to 7 years old, and she's perfected the art of guilting people into babysitting. I've fallen for it way too many times, always telling myself I'd say no next time. Yesterday, around three in the afternoon, I heard aggressive knocking. I peeked through the window and saw Amber, so I stayed quiet, hoping she'd leave. The knocking got louder. She started hitting the door so hard I thought she'd rip a letterbox off. I opened the door, and she immediately started talking at lightning speed. Something about an emergency. She'd be back Sunday. The cab was waiting. She was so sorry. Before I could process what was happening, I noticed all six of her kids standing behind her with overnight bags. Wait, I can't watch them, I said firmly. The black cabs running. I have to go right now. I'll be back Sunday, I promise. She was already backing away. I tried grabbing her arm. Amber, I'm serious. I have plans this weekend. She yanked free and literally sprinted to the waiting cab. I stood there in shock as she drove off, leaving six children on my porch. The baby started crying. The seven year old looked at me and asked if we Had snacks. I was beyond furious. I brought the kids inside and waited 40 minutes, giving her time to come to her senses. Then I texted, you have 10 minutes to turn around and get your kids or I'm calling child services. No response. I called her straight to voicemail. Called again, voicemail. On my third call, she finally picked up. What? She nap. Come get your kids right now or I'm calling child services. I'm not joking. Oh, my god, you're being so dramatic. I'm already out of the city. I can't come back. Just drop them off at Marilyn's house if you don't want them. Marilyn is 68 years old with health problems. She can't handle six kids. Then I guess you're watching them. I'll be back Sunday. She hung up. I stared at my phone in disbelief. Then I called child services. The woman who answered was professional and calm. I explained everything. That a neighbor abandoned her children at my house, refused to return, and expected me to care for them for four days. She said a social worker would arrive within the hour. While I waited, something occurred to me. I set up my phone on the mantle and started recording. When the social worker pulled up thirty minutes later, I captured everything. The social worker, a kind woman named Patricia, showed her badge and asked me to explain the situation. I told her everything while the camera rolled. She interviewed me, checked on the Kids made several phone calls. The whole process took about 20 minutes. Finally, she said, we'll need to take them into temporary custody until we can reach the mother. I watched as Patricia gently explained to the kids that they were going somewhere safe. The seven year old started crying. My heart broke, but I reminded myself, this wasn't my fault. Amber did this to her own children. As Patricia buckled the last car seat, I stopped recording. I had 12 minutes of footage. I trimmed it down to the key moments. Patricia showing her badge, me explain that their mother refused to return, and the kids being escorted to the county van. I texted the video to Amber with one message. They're at the county services office waiting for you to pick them up. Thirty seconds later, my phone started exploding. Call after call from Amber. I declined every single one. Then the text started rolling in. Answer your phone. What did you do, you evil person? Call me!

Sir, our system shows three separate key card entries today while you were out. None of them were your card. I look around my room. Everything seemed normal. Are you sure it's not a glitch? I've worked here 11 years. Woman said, this isn't a glitch. Someone has a key card to your room. She sounds extremely worried. I looked at the man's photo and recognized him instantly. It's the man from the hotel bar last night. British accent, friendly. He bought me a drink. But why was his suitcase in my closet? His suitcase was in my room, his passport, his wallet. Who checks out without those? The woman stared at me like she had no answers. I headed back upstairs without waiting. I needed to know more. Sir, you need to come with us now. They put me in Handcuffs. I spent the next six hours in a concrete interrogation room. Cold grey. A detective sat across from me, asking the same questions over and over. You were seen talking to Mister Puck at the bar. He bought me a drink. We talked. That's it. voice_to_text: My family ignored me when I said I moved to Arizona. 10 months later, mom called screaming, why didn't you tell us? I said I did six times. I sent the first text in March. Dad never opened it. I thought maybe they were busy, so I tried again at Sunday dinner. Got guys, I'm moving to Phoenix on the 15th! My mom was scrolling her phone. That's nice, honey. Vanessa was facetiming her boyfriend in the corner. Dad grunted something about needing help moving his grill next weekend. I sat there, fork halfway to my mouth, realizing none of them had actually heard me. The week before I left, I posted in the family group chat. Last chance to say goodbye before Arizona. Anyone wanna grab dinner? Vanessa replied, asking if I could pick up her dry cleaning since I was still in town. Mom asked if I'd seen her post about her book club on Facebook. I picked up the dry cleaning the day I left. I texted one final time, driving to Arizona today. New address attached. Love you all. 12 hours later, my mom reacted with a heart emoji. That was it. The first month in Phoenix was chaos. New job, new apartment, making friends, learning which highways actually moved during Rush hour. I called home twice. Both times, I got voicemail. I left messages mentioning Arizona, my new neighborhood, the eat. No one called back. By month three, I stopped trying so hard. I'd text holiday greetings, send photos of desert sunsets. My family's responses were generic. Beautiful, miss you. Vanessa sent me TikToks she thought were funny, but never asked how I was doing. I started building a real life, found a hiking group, dated someone, briefly got promoted again at work. Arizona stopped feeling temporary and started feeling like home. Then, 10 months after I moved, my phone exploded. At 6:00am on a Tuesday, 17 missed calls from my mother, a voicemail that was just screaming. Three texts in all caps. I called back, still half asleep. Why didn't you tell us you moved? Mom shrieked before I could say hello. What are you talking about? I told you six times. You did not! I would remember my son moving across the country. March 4th, I texted everyone. March 10th, I brought it up at Sunday dinner. March 18th, I posted in the group chat. March 22nd, I texted my new address. You never said a word. That's not true! She snapped. I felt something cold settle in my chest. Why are you calling me now? Your sister's getting married in two weeks. We need you here for photos. The venue is already booked. Vanessa can't reach you. I live in Arizona, mom. I've lived here for 10 months. It's a five Hour flight. This is ridiculous. She said, just get on a plane. I'm in the middle of a huge project at work. I can't just leave. You're choosing work over family? No, I'm choosing the life I built after my family ignored me for almost a year. That afternoon, Vanessa called, furious. Mom says you're refusing to come to my wedding. I didn't even know you were engaged. I posted about it six months ago. Did you comment? Did you call? Did you acknowledge it at all? Silence!

voice_to_text: I asked my dad for a new sweatshirt and his reaction broke my heart. I'm 16 and I guess you could call me a late bloomer. Over the past year my shoulders finally broadened out and I shot up about four inches. None of my clothes fit anymore. I've been wearing the same five stretched out shirts for months and three of them have actual tears in the seams. My dad's 37. He had me when he was 21, right after getting out of a three year stint. He never finished high school, got in with a bad crowd in his neighborhood, made some stupid choices. My mom left when I was a baby. He told me she just couldn't handle being a parent. I tried reaching out to her on Facebook one but she blocked me immediately. We live in my grandparents old single wide trailer on about half an acre of their land. They passed when I was seven and my dad inherited it. The trailer isn't much, the AC barely works, the floor is soft in some spots and you can hear everything through the walls. But it's ours and my dad keeps it clean. He works construction for a local company. He's tried moving up for years, but his record and lack of education keep blocking him. He makes about $15 an hour and between the bills, his debt payments and keeping food on the table, there's not much left over. Last time I got new Clothes was my 15th birthday. Dad used his entire stimulus check to take me shopping at Walmart. I got six shirts, three pairs of jeans, some socks. I remember how happy he looked watching me try stuff on. But now nothing fits. The shirts hurt my shoulders and the sleeves cut into my arms. I tried stealing some from the lost and found at school. Well, but I'm bigger than most kids my age, and nothing worked. My dad refuses to let me get a job. I've asked him probably 10 times, and every time he gets this angry look and says he's not gonna have his own kid providing for him. He stopped his entire life for me. Never dated anyone, never took a vacation. Just worked and came home to make sure I had dinner and help with homework. Last night during dinner, we were eating spaghetti and watching some game show. I finally worked up the courage to ask dad, do you think we could maybe get a sweatshirt or two just from Walmart or something? His face completely fell. He set down his fork and got this look I'd never seen before. Like I just reminded him of something he was dead desperately trying to forget. He explained really gently that we didn't have the money right now. The truck needed new tires, we had to restock groceries, and his insurance payment was coming up. But he promised he'd start putting aside $10 here and there. And maybe in a few months we could go shopping. I felt this wave of disappointment and guilt. Me at the same time. I told him it was fine, don't worry about it. And went to my room. That's when I heard it. Through the paper thin walls, my dad was crying. Not just tearing up. Actually saw bobbing. I could hear him trying to muffle it. But in our trailer, you hear everything. I've seen my dad cry maybe twice in my entire life. Once when his mom died, and once when I showed him my report card with straight A's for the first time. I wanted to walk out there and hug him, tell him it's okay, that I didn't need anything. But I've never been good with emotions. Just sat on my bed listening to him cry, feeling like the worst son in the world for even asking. Eventually, I fell asleep. This morning, I woke up and walked into the kitchen. There was a note on the table in my dad's messy handwriting. Had to leave early for a job in the next town.

voice_to_text: I found my boss's performance review for me in the printer. Lazy, entitled, always on his phone. I said nothing, just started documenting everything. Six months later, he called me into his office with HR. I've been working as a junior analyst at Michelin Cross for three years. The pay was decent, work was straightforward, and I actually enjoyed what I did. But my boss, Derek, had this way of making me feel like I was constantly failing, even when I wasn't. He'd walk past my desk without acknowledging me for days. Then suddenly, when a client complained or a report was late, I'd be pulled into his office for a lecture about accountability and professionalism. It didn't matter if the mistake was actually his or someone else's. I was the easiest target. One Tuesday afternoon, I walked to the shared printer on our floor to grab some contract copies I'd sent over. The machine was still warm, spitting out pages. And there, face up on the tray, was a document with my name at the top. Employee performance review confidential. I glanced around. The floor was quiet. Most people were at lunch. I picked it up and started reading Derek's notes. Shows up late. Constantly spends half the day on personal calls and texting. Barely meets minimum standards. Does not take initiative. Recommend no raise this cycle. Possible PIP if behavior continues. My stomach dropped. I read it again, slower this time, thinking maybe I'd misunderstood. But no, it Was right there. Black ink on white paper. The thing is, none of it was true. I've been arriving at least 15 minutes early every single day for the past year. I made coffee, prepped reports, answered early emails before anyone else even got in. My phone usage was almost entirely work related. Tracking project updates in our client portal or coordinating with the sales team and performance. I'd closed more accounts in the last quarter than anyone else on the team. Three major clients had specifically requested to work with me again. I stood there holding that paper hand, shaking not from sadness, but from pure anger. I took a photo with my phone. Then I put the document back exactly where I found it and walk back to my desk. That's when I decided. No confrontation, no emotional outburst. Cold, detailed evidence. I started keeping receipts on everything. Every email I sent, I bcc to my personal account with time stamps. Every client win, I documented with confirmations and thank you notes. Every morning I arrived early. I sent myself a photo of the office clock showing the time. I tracked Derek's schedule, too. The two hour lunches while I covered his client calls. The days he left at 3 for meetings that didn't exist. I saved the Slack message where he told me to lie to a client about why a deliverable was late, a deadline he'd missed. Not me. I kept a spreadsheet. Dates, times, evidence, Six months of my actual work compared to his false narrative. My folder grew thick with proof. Then one morning in March, Derek's assistant messaged me. Derek needs to see you in conference room B at two PM. HR will be there. My heart rate spiked, but I stayed calm. I knew what this was. At two PM, I walked in. Derek sat on one side of the table, arms crossed, looking annoyed. Across from him was Monica from HR, laptop open expression neutral and professional. Have a seat, Monica said.

voice_to_text: Next morning changed everything. Instead of waking up at 6:30 to start his coffee and lay out his clothes, I rolled over and went back to sleep. At 7:30, I heard him stumbling around. Where's the coffee? Where's my blue shirt? I stretched lazily. You mean your stuff? Remember what you said? We're splitting everything 50 50. Now that means we each handle our own responsibilities, but you always make coffee. I make coffee for myself. You're welcome to make your own. I headed for my closet. Your blue shirt is in the dirty clothes basket where you left it three days ago. Your clothes are your responsibility now. This is ridiculous, he muttered. You're being petty. I'm being practical just like you said I was. Then came the real education when he ruined my 95 dollar blouse by throwing his red gym shirt in with my whites. I presented him with a Bill. Property damage, your negligence, your responsibility. Over the next weeks, I implemented a comprehensive damage system. Coffee rings on the table I'd refinished. 15 dollar restoration fee using my expensive shampoo. Twelve dollar replacement cost. Eating my Greek yogurt, seven dollars and thirty eight cents plus inconvenience fee. But the truth came crashing down when I came home early one Thursday, I heard him on the phone. Whole splitting expenses thing is going better than I expected. Once I get her paying half of everything, I'll have way more money to help with your rent and The kids stuff. She's been playing housewife for 7 years. It's about time she contributed something real. He'd been funding his ex girlfriend's life while keeping me as unpaid household labor. Instead of confronting him immediately, I got strategic, started applying for jobs, dusted off my old LinkedIn and within two months landed a consulting contract that paid more per month than he made in two. When I told him the salary, his eyes widened. That's more than I make. I know. I smiled. Looks like I won't have any trouble paying my half after all. The lawsuit came next. He tried to evict me from my own home for creating an inhabitable living situation by not doing his laundry. The judge reviewed my evidence, his spreadsheet, the bank transfers to his ex and meticulous records of his double standards. Petition denied. The judge said firmly the evidence suggests she has been remarkably accommodating to an arrangement heavily biased against her interests. I moved out anyway, got my own apartment with big windows and hardwood floors, started dating my colleague, Jake, who never once made me feel like my worth was up for negotiation. Six months later, my ex showed up at my office. I've changed, he said. I Learned to cook, clean, do my own laundry. I get it now. Please give me another chance. I just ignored.

voice_to_text: My husband of seven years demanded that we split all the household bills because he said so. I've been thinking, he said, not looking up from the chicken I'd spent an hour preparing. Things need to change around here. I've been doing some math, he continued, and this arrangement isn't fair to me anymore. I work my ass off every day while you do whatever this is. He gestured vaguely around our immaculate kitchen. The words hit like ice water. I left my marketing job seven years ago when we got married. His idea, actually. A man should provide for his wife, he said back then. I want to take care of you now. He was looking at me like I was a parasite. I've created a spreadsheet, I said, flipping open the laptop with the enthusiasm of someone presenting a brilliant business proposal. From now on, we're splitting everything fifty fifty. The screen showed our life reduced to numbers. Mortgage, $2,947, utilities, $340. Groceries, $580. Insurance, $420. But I don't have a job, I said quietly. You asked me to quit, remember? He waved dismissively. That was then. This is now. You're smart. You can figure something out. I'm not running a charity here. I stared at this man, whose socks I've been washing, whose meals I've been cooking, whose mother I've been tolerating for seven years. Something shifted inside me, something cold and sharp. So let me understand, I said, my voice taking on a tone I barely Recognized you want me to pay half of everything. Starting when? Starting next month. I, I knew you'd be reasonable about this. I looked at the spreadsheet again, noting every detail. Okay, I said, you're absolutely right. If we're going to be roommates instead of husband and wife, we should split everything equally. His surprise was obvious. He'd expected tears, begging. Instead, he got agreement. And it clearly unsettled him. The next morning changed everything.

voice_to_text: My husband of seven years demanded that we split all the household bills because he said so. I've been thinking, he said, not looking up from the chicken I'd spent an hour preparing. Things need to change around here. I've been doing some math, he continued, and this arrangement isn't fair to me anymore. I work my ass off every day while you do whatever this is. He gestured vaguely around our immaculate kitchen. The words hit like ice water. I left my marketing job seven years ago when we got married. His idea, actually. A man should provide for his wife, he said back then. I want to take care of you now. He was looking at me like I was a parasite. I've created a spreadsheet, I said, flipping open the laptop with the enthusiasm of someone presenting a brilliant business proposal. From now on, we're splitting everything fifty fifty. The screen showed our life reduced to numbers. Mortgage, $2,947, utilities, $340. Groceries, $580. Insurance, $420. But I don't have a job, I said quietly. You asked me to quit, remember? He waved dismissively. That was then. This is now. You're smart. You can figure something out. I'm not running a charity here. I stared at this man, whose socks I've been washing, whose meals I've been cooking, whose mother I've been tolerating for seven years. Something shifted inside me, something cold and sharp. So let me understand, I said, my voice taking on a tone I barely Recognized you want me to pay half of everything. Starting when? Starting next month. I knew you'd be reasonable about this. I looked at the spreadsheet again, noting every detail. Okay, I said, you're absolutely right. If we're going to be roommates instead of husband and wife, we should split everything equally. His surprise was obvious. He'd expected tears, begging. Instead, he got agreement. And it clearly unsettled him.

voice_to_text: On her first night shift, the nurse suddenly got slapped out of nowhere. When she stood up and looked around, there was not a soul in sight. She went to the mirror, staring at the clear handprint on her face, certain it hadn't been a dream. Just as she figured it was a prank by a colleague, something unexpected happened. The story takes place in a hospital in Mexico. On her first day of work, Sophia was assigned to work the night shift alone in the intensive care ICU. The head nurse handed her the keys and warned her if she encountered any other nurses during the night shift, she must not speak to them. After Sophia left, one nurse said they should tell her the truth, but the head nurse clearly had no intention of doing so. When Sophia arrived at the ICU, the empty corridor genuinely gave her the creeps. She summoned up her courage and started working. At first, everything went smoothly, but just as she was about to change a patient's dressing, she suddenly heard singing coming from the corridor. Sophia cautiously stepped out to check, but the corridor was completely empty. No one was there. She reassured herself she must have misheard, put on a brave face and returned to the ward. her distraction made her accidentally knock over the medical solution, staining her clothes. Sophia had to go back to the staff locker room, only to find her locker door already open as She wondered why the sound of high heeled shoes suddenly echoed in the corridor and a figure appeared behind the glass. Sophia tentatively greeted the figure, but there was no response. She plucked up the courage to step out and check, but the corridor was still deserted. Just as she was changing her clothes, the footsteps sounded again. Peering out from behind the locker, she saw the figure wearing a nurse's cap, moving stiffly like a zombie. Sophia froze in terror, staring fixedly at the figure which seemed about to walk into the locker room at any moment. Yet in the next second, it vanished without a trace. Sophia didn't believe in ghosts, so she thought these bizarre incidents were definitely pranks by her colleagues, teasing the new girl. She didn't have time to think further, as the patient was still waiting for her to administer an injection. Sophia hurried back to the ward. When she was about to give a man a painkiller, he said a nurse in a black cloak had already given it to him earlier. Sophia quickly checked the records and found an unfamiliar signature had indeed been added and some of the painkillers in the tray were missing. Furious at her colleague's extreme behavior, she stormed to the nurses station to confront them. However, the colleague replied that only Sophia had the keys to the ICU. She couldn't have gotten in at all. Moreover, black cloaks were worn by nurses 100 years ago and had Long been phased out, the colleague solemnly warned her the ICU had always been haunted, so she must not fall asleep during the night shift. Sophia stood frozen, suddenly regretting taking the job. As she returned to the ICU with a heavy heart, the lights in the corridor began to flicker violently, the sound of footsteps mixed with singing echoed again, and an eerie black figure slowly emerged from the corner. Sophia summoned all her courage and walked forward slowly. She wanted to see what the ghost really looked like.

voice_to_text: I looked at the pizza in my hand. I noticed that the toppings had been eaten by someone from the upper level. So I thought about taking someone else's food. However, as soon as I picked up a piece of chicken wing, Tony from the upper level stopped me, told me I could only eat my own food. This was the rule of the loyalists because if someone steals food, it means the people below will go hungry. I explained that my pizza had been eaten by someone else. Tony said they would solve the problem for me, and he told me not to break the rules. If I insisted on stealing someone else's food, I would be punished by the loyalists. I didn't want to hear their explanation. I just wanted to compensate myself immediately. But then my cellmate Jenny stopped me. She gave me her croquette to eat, so I finally put the chicken wing back. The next day, we heard fighting from upstairs. Four members from the 19th and 20th floors came down to the 21st floor to punish the one who stole my pizza. But the four of them couldn't even beat the opponent. This meant the thief had strong combat abilities. Tony from upstairs told me that if they couldn't beat that person, Jenny and I would need to prepare for a fight. Hearing this, I immediately gave up and lied, saying I never fought. But as soon as I finished speaking, the platform arrived. Upstairs, Tony and Laura immediately started fighting. Seeing this, Jenny quickly lifted the mattress, then took out an iron bar from the bed frame to prepare for the enemy. When the platform came down, I was stunned. I saw a corpse quietly lying on it. This should be the punishment for someone from the 21st floor who broke the rules. I couldn't help but feel scared, because if I had eaten the chicken wing yesterday, I would have received the same punishment today. Before I could react, I saw Laura from upstairs frantically kicking the food down. But she was still one step too late, because she had secretly kept food. This caused the temperature on her floor to rise sharply and she was burned alive and dropped down. Jenny tried to use a bed sheet to extinguish the fire, but it was too late. In an instant, Laura was burned to a charred corpse. By the time I reacted, platform started moving down to the next floor. Tony told us to quickly clear the food, and the room returned to its normal temperature. Because of the thief's disregard for the rules, today's food could not be eaten in the fight, so the people below had no food to eat. From the third day on, I began to follow the rules. I only ate my own pizza every day. To enforce the rules strictly, Tony threw away all the food from the people who died yesterday. But on this day, After eating pizza for more than 20 days straight, I suddenly had an idea. I pretended to throw away the food and secretly grabbed a piece of food and stuffed it in my mouth. But this scene was noticed by the people above. However, they didn't expose me. Soon, it was time to change floors. Good news came from downstairs that food could be delivered intact to the one hundred and seventy fifth floor. Jenny and I happily started dancing, but when we woke up the next day, we found we had been assigned to the one hundred and eightieth floor, the floor where food had never reached.

His job was to help a different woman fall asleep every night, but he wasn't selling his body at all. What he truly offered was comfort and calm. As the company's top ranked sleep companion, Nilo had to obey three unbreakable rules, no unbuttoning a client's clothes, no reacting to flirtatious talk and absolutely no dozing off himself. With touch free soothing and aromatherapy, most clients drifted off within minutes. But tonight he received an unusual request. Taylor booked a full four hour session in one go. Nilo showered, changed into pajamas and settled into the bed as usual. But Taylor suddenly seemed anxious. Sticking to the routine, Nilo guided her to lie on her side. Yet Taylor's body kept sliding closer. He sensed it instantly, gently pushing her away and stacking two pillows to keep distance. Taylor exploded. How could a sleep companion act so aloof? She stormed into the living room demanding a refund. Reluctantly, Nilo started calculating the charges. Sandwiches, essential oils, drinks, toiletries, plus service fees. In the end, he could only give her back $500. Taylor grew even more frustrated. Since the money was spent, she might as well finish the night. Back in bed, Nilo resumed the aromatherapy and fitted her eye mask. But Taylor couldn't stay quiet for even three seconds before speaking up again. Act normal. I can't fall asleep like this. Nero's face tightened. He wanted to talk over fast, but Taylor kept going. Can you take the glove off? Feels Weird. Nero reluctantly complied. No one expected what happened next. The company's star sleep coach actually fell asleep at her place, a direct violation of all three rules. Nilo apologized non stop, begging Taylor not to leave a bad review. He rushed back to the office to confess only for his boss to praise him instead. Taylor had not only left five stars, but booked him for the entire month. Over the next weeks, Nilo accompanied her night after night. He Learned Taylor had just ended a ten year relationship and the pain hit him, too. Even when serving other clients, his mind drifted to Taylor's social posts. He had fallen for someone he shouldn't. Tonight was the final session. Taylor cooked him an elaborate dinner and they talked about everything from the news to late night shows until the mood subtly shifted. They leaned closer and closer when suddenly Nelo's phone rang.

voice_to_text: Every time she dipped her hand into the crystal clear ocean, thousands of fish swarmed around her. The fisherman weren't surprised anymore when never she joined them on their boats. They never returned empty handed. Her gift fed the entire island. But that wasn't the only miracle. Every morning a long line formed outside her house. People whispered that a single touch from her could heal anything. Cuts vanished in an instant. Aches faded away. Soon the villagers treated her like a living goddess. Then one day everything changed. She went to the mountains with her friends where they discovered a massive beehive. As she approached, the furious buzzing stopped. The bees landed softly on her palm, bowing as if she were their queen. Thrilled, she turned to show her friends only to see horror unfold. The bees had attacked. One of them panicked. She clenched her fist and in that single motion, every bee dropped dead. Frozen with fear, she realised what had happened. She thought everyone would now see her as a monster. She made her friends swear never to tell a soul. From that day on, her powers began to fade. Her touch could no longer heal. The fisherman caught fewer fish and the villagers were left bewildered, unable to understand what had happened to their miracle girl.

voice_to_text: The entire institute is plunged into shock and grief, grief because a longtime friend was on that vessel, shock because a massive research ship shouldn't go down for no reason. Not until they watch the rescue footage where the sunken vessel is encircled by a glowing white ring and sharp, piercing noises echo all around it. Even the veteran professor who spent decades studying the sea has never seen anything like this, let alone the intern, Kelly. Yet unexpectedly, Kelly is the one who uncovers the cause of the accident. Back at the coastal station, she finds a video message left by her friend before the disaster, but she missed it because she was out drinking that night. The guilt of losing her last chance to speak to her best friend crushes her. But soon she notices something unusual in the video. Right before the recording ends, a white light rises outside the window, the same glow as the deep sea light paired with the same shrill noise. To test her theory, Kelly extracts both audio samples, the one from the message and the one from the deep. The comparison shows they match almost perfectly. Kelly concludes the shipwreck is tied to these strange signals. She immediately reports her findings to the old professor, but this is far beyond what the professor can accept. She refuses to believe anything supernatural exists in the ocean. Their argument escalates and they part on bad terms. However, Professor Seagle overhears and makes a New discovery. When he gets home, he receives whale footage sent by kit comparing the two. The same white light and bizarre noise appear again. Tests confirm the match. The professor realizes she wrongfully blamed Kelly. Too proud to apologize herself, she asks Seagull to deliver the footage to Kelly on his way to a global ocean conference. Seagull acknowledges Kelly's findings. The tension between Kelly and the professor finally eases. They are getting closer to the truth. But as Kelly walks Seagull to the helicopter, a catastrophe of unprecedented scale erupts. Because the bearded researcher running experiments notices everyone's phones suddenly start ringing. He checks his own and sees a tsunami emergency alert. Kelly City is listed among the three danger zones. He calls her immediately, but Kelly didn't bring her phone while seeing Seagull off. Luckily, just before take off, Seagull receives the institute's emergency warning. He drags Kelly away from the danger zone. Minutes later, the tsunami slams into the coast. Watching her entire station wiped out so effortlessly leaves Kelly trembling. At least she is alive. Others aren't so fortunate. Blocks of seabirds suddenly flee inland in panic and the shoreline retreats dramatically. Anyone who has lived through a tsunami knows this is the omen of a coming catastrophe. People sprint wildly. Drivers slam the gas. Those on foot wish they could grow wings, but nothing can outrun the fury of the sea. Three coastal nations are struck simultaneously. The Global Ocean Organization immediately takes action. During the emergency summit, a virologist speech shocks every top scientist present, and they realize a threat far more terrifying than the tsunami is rapidly approaching.

voice_to_text: A young woman ordered a luxury meal, but the moment she lifted the lid, her heart nearly stopped. The box was completely empty and even the receipt was blank. Furious, she tried calling the restaurant, only to find the number didn't connect at all. Confused and uneasy, she noticed a strange note inside. Write down any food you want and place it in the box. Thinking it had to be a joke, she played along, scribbled barbecue on a slip of paper and tossed it inside. Seconds later, the box rattled violently and burst with a flash of white light. When it stopped shaking, real steaming barbecue sat inside. One bite told her everything. This wasn't a prank. It was magic. Greed quickly took over. She swapped the paper and requested sushi, and fresh sushi materialized instantly, dish after exotic dish. She pushed the box to its limits and a bold thought hit her. What's the priciest food on earth? A quick search told her caviar, worth nearly $1,000 per spoonful. Her note was full, so she grabbed the nearest item, a supplement box, wrote caviar on it and placed it inside the magic container. the box trembled again and real caviar appeared right before her eyes. She immediately jumped online to brag about tasting such an extravagant delicacy. But midpost, her nose began to bleed, her vision blurred. Moments later, she collapsed, foaming at the mouth. The horrifying truth, the package she wrote on didn't just say supplement It clearly warned poison. The box didn't produce what she wanted. It produced exactly what she wrote on. And this time it killed her.
